The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business

 Mint merger gets go-ahead

 OUR SPECIAL CORRESPONDENT

 New Delhi, Sept. 2: The government decided at a cabinet meeting today to merge all its security presses, mints and paper mills into one corporation ? Security Printing amp; Minting Corporation of India.

 The move aims at improving the productivity and financial performance of these mints and presses. The government will give Rs 700 crore interest-free loan for the working capital of the corporation.

 Nine organisations under the economic affairs department of the finance ministry will be transferred to the new corporation. It has been decided to integrate all these nine organisations into one corporation, defence minister Pranab Mukherjee told reporters after the cabinet meeting.

 The corporation will come into effect from October 1 or any such date decided by the government, Mukherjee said. Four mints, including the Alipore Mint, four security presses and one security paper mill will be transferred to the Security Printing amp; Minting Corporation of India, Mukherjee said. 

 The corporation will take over the assets, liabilities, functions and employees of all the nine units as on September 30.

 Mukherjee said the corporation would take over the existing employees of the units on the existing terms and conditions, initially on deputation basis for two years within which they will exercise their option for absorption in the newly formed corporation.

 The corporatisation process is aimed at overall improvement in decision making, operational flexibility, coupled with commensurate accountability, efficiency and higher productivity of the units, the minister said.

 He said the manpower and managerial deployment would be optimised and promotion policies, rewards and remuneration structure would be linked to performance and productivity.

 Wireless solutions

 The cabinet today approved the setting up of a Rs 212-crore research centre in Chennai as a joint venture project between C-DoT and Alcatel. It will develop broadband wireless solutions on WiMAX technology. WiMax (802.16 standards) is a group broadband wireless communications standards for metropolitan area network developed by the Institute of Electrical and Electronics Engineers. 




